===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{liushu|p}} – hand and fingers. The top stroke is the bent over middle finger, while the horizontal strokes are each two fingers. Compare {{zh-m|*爪}}, {{zh-m|*寸}}, {{zh-m|*九}}, {{zh-m|*又}}, and {{zh-m|*彐}} as a stylized hand. Compare {{zh-m|*丑}} as an animal claw. See also the bottom part of {{zh-m|*舉}} and {{zh-m|*奉}}.

Note that unlike the other hand/claw characters, {{lang|zh|手}} has consistently had five fingers: a mammalian/human hand, as opposed to the three digits often found in the others.

Compare also {{zh-m|*止|foot}}, derived from a footprint pointing upward, originally composed of 3 toes and a sole.

===Etymology===
STEDT compares this word to {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*g-(t)sjəw-k/ŋ||wing; hand}} based on Karlgren's Archaic Chinese ({{cog|och|-}}) reconstruction ''*śi̯ôg'', connecting it to {{cog|bo|གཤོག||wing}}.

However, this comparison is not supported by more recent scholarship, in which the {{cog|och|-}} is reconstructed with an alveolar nasal ({{zh-ref|Unger, 1995}}; {{zh-ref|Zhengzhang, 1995}}; {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart, 2014}}). Evidence for the nasal initial is given in {{zh-ref|Sagart (1999)}}:
* {{zh-m|*杻|handcuffs}} can be written as {{zh-m|*杽}}, so {{och-l|丑|tr=*ᵇhnruʔ}} (with a nasal initial) and {{lang|zh|手}} seem to be interchangeable as phonetics.
* The ancient graph {{zh-m|*丑}} resembles the graph of {{zh-m|*又|right hand}}. {{och-l|狃|tr=*ᵇnruʔ|animal track; claw}} seems to be the modern specialized form of {{zh-m|*丑}}, which has been borrowed to represent an [[earthly branch]].

As done by {{zh-ref|Sagart (1999)}}, {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart (2014)}} put {{och-l|杻|tr=*n̥<r>uʔ|handcuffs}} and {{och-l|狃|tr=*Cə.n<r>uʔ |animal track; claw}} into the same word family as {{och-l|手|tr=*n̥uʔ}}. {{zh-ref|Zhengzhang (1995)}} suggests a connection to the {{m|my||ညှိုး}} in {{cog|my|လက်ညှိုး||forefinger}}, which STEDT derives from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-njuŋ ~ *s-m-juŋ ~ *s-m-juw||finger}}. See {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*C-njuʔ|t=finger}} for more.

Alternatively, {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} suggests a tone B [[endoactive]] derivation from {{och-l|收|tr=*nhiu?|to take; to gather}}, literally “that which is doing the taking”.

